BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:john-hansard-gallery-disabled-artists-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260521T105355Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260525
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260526
SUMMARY:Deadline: John Hansard Gallery: Open Call for Disabled Artists 2026
  (Future Curators)
DESCRIPTION:Open call from John Hansard Gallery for one disabled artist to 
 collaborate with Occupational Therapy and Engineering students at the Univ
 ersity of Southampton to make or adapt tools that support their artistic p
 ractice. The tools and resulting artwork are displayed in an exhibition at
  John Hansard Gallery in February 2027\, curated by Jess Starns as part of
  the Future Curators Programme\, a disability-justice residency programme 
 for Disabled curators founded by the Disabled artist-led organisation DASH
 . The work involves collaborating with students in July and August\, testi
 ng and refining the tools through autumn\, and creating artwork for the ex
 hibition. ELIGIBILITY: disabled artists living and working within a 40-mil
 e distance of John Hansard Gallery. Submit an Expression of Interest via t
 he gallery's open-call page\; access requirements supported (contact jenni
 fa@jhg.art).\n\nOrganisation: John Hansard Gallery\, with the University o
 f Southampton (part of the DASH Future Curators Programme)\nLocation: With
 in 40 miles of John Hansard Gallery\, Southampton\, UK\nAward: GBP 2\,000 
 artist fee (including up to four meetings with students)\, plus travel exp
 enses\, access costs and a materials budget to be defined. No application 
 fee.\nDuration: Project running July 2026 to a February 2027 exhibition\n\
 nMore: https://jhg.art/events/open-call-disabled-artists/
URL:https://jhg.art/events/open-call-disabled-artists/
LOCATION:Within 40 miles of John Hansard Gallery\, Southampton\, UK
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:vas-bothy-project-sweeneys-bothy-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260521T105355Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260614
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260615
SUMMARY:Deadline: Visual Arts Scotland x Bothy Project: Sweeney's Bothy Res
 idency 2026 (Isle of Eigg)
DESCRIPTION:Sixth year of Visual Arts Scotland's residency in partnership w
 ith Bothy Project\, offering a week at Sweeney's Bothy\, an off-grid\, pur
 pose-built artist residency space on the Isle of Eigg in the Scottish Inne
 r Hebrides. As the residency is only a week long\, there is no expectation
  to produce a body of work\; the purpose is time to reflect on practice\, 
 develop ideas and engage with the island's environment and culture. ELIGIB
 ILITY: open to any creative discipline (visual arts\, craft and design\, m
 usic\, literature\, performance\, and researchers/thinkers)\, but applican
 ts must be a VAS member at both the time of application and the time of re
 sidency. Applicants are asked to be mindful of the island community's etho
 s of environmental sustainability and to travel sustainably (cars are not 
 permitted for non-residents). The successful applicant undertakes a VAS In
 stagram takeover and documents their experience. Apply by email to admin@v
 isualartsscotland.org plus the online form\, with six images of recent wor
 k on a single PDF.\n\nOrganisation: Visual Arts Scotland (VAS)\, in partne
 rship with Bothy Project\nLocation: Sweeney's Bothy\, Isle of Eigg\, Scott
 ish Inner Hebrides\, UK (off-grid)\nAward: GBP 720 artist fee\, plus reaso
 nable travel up to GBP 250 and accommodation costs included. No applicatio
 n fee.\nDuration: One-week residency (10 to 17 October 2026)\n\nMore: http
 s://www.visualartsscotland.org/opportunity/bothy-project-residency-2026/
URL:https://www.visualartsscotland.org/opportunity/bothy-project-residency-
 2026/
LOCATION:Sweeney's Bothy\, Isle of Eigg\, Scottish Inner Hebrides\, UK (off
 -grid)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:decoratelier-workspacebrussels-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.
 io
DTSTAMP:20260521T105355Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260531
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260601
SUMMARY:Deadline: workspacebrussels: Decoratelier Open Call 2026 (Spatial R
 esearch Residency)
DESCRIPTION:Research-focused residency at Decoratelier in Molenbeek\, organ
 ised through workspacebrussels\, for artists and collectives working with 
 space\, scenography\, installation\, architecture and performative environ
 ments. The residency prioritises research and material experimentation ove
 r production: applicants propose an investigation into spatial practice\, 
 ephemeral architecture or scenographic experimentation connected to the pe
 rforming arts\, engaging directly with the warehouse architecture and reus
 able materials. ELIGIBILITY: artists or collectives based in Belgium or ab
 road. NOTE: this is a context-specific research residency and does not pro
 vide scenographic support for existing productions. Apply via the workspac
 ebrussels Decoratelier open call.\n\nOrganisation: workspacebrussels (resi
 dency at Decoratelier\, Molenbeek)\nLocation: Decoratelier\, Molenbeek\, B
 russels\, Belgium\nAward: EUR 5\,000 budget (incl. VAT) for the residency\
 , plus a 10x18m warehouse hall\, wood and metal workshop access\, reusable
  materials\, junior-builder support three days a week\, artistic and techn
 ical feedback\, a possible internal showing\, and weekday lunch. No applic
 ation fee.\nDuration: Three-week research residency (5 to 23 October 2026)
 \n\nMore: https://www.workspacebrussels.be/en
URL:https://www.workspacebrussels.be/en
LOCATION:Decoratelier\, Molenbeek\, Brussels\, Belgium
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mdd-collective-open-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260521T105355Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260614
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260615
SUMMARY:Deadline: Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens: MDD Collective Open Call 2026
DESCRIPTION:Open call from Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens' youth collective invitin
 g three to four emerging artists to present a work in the museum garden ov
 er the weekend of 11-12 July 2026\, in dialogue with its surroundings\, ar
 chitecture and landscape. The theme centres on the idea of the 'frame'\, s
 tarting from Isa Genzken's work Fenster in the museum garden\, exploring h
 ow a frame determines what we see and what stays just outside our field of
  vision. ELIGIBILITY: emerging artists aged 31 or under interested in join
 ing MDD's youth project. Apply via the Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens open-call pa
 ge\; questions to opencall@museumdd.be.\n\nOrganisation: Museum Dhondt-Dha
 enens (MDD) youth collective\nLocation: Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens garden\, Si
 nt-Martens-Latem\, Belgium (outdoor presentation)\nAward: EUR 500 material
  budget plus a EUR 350 participation fee per selected artist\; transport a
 nd insurance of the works are fully covered by the organisation. No applic
 ation fee.\nDuration: One-weekend presentation (11-12 July 2026)\n\nMore: 
 https://museumdd.be/en/event/open-call-mdd-collective
URL:https://museumdd.be/en/event/open-call-mdd-collective
LOCATION:Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens garden\, Sint-Martens-Latem\, Belgium (outd
 oor presentation)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:jan-van-eyck-material-research-fellowships-2027@artificialnouveau.githu
 b.io
DTSTAMP:20260521T105355Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260624
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260625
SUMMARY:Deadline: Jan van Eyck Academie: Material Research Fellowships 2027
  (Future Materials)
DESCRIPTION:Two material-research fellowships at the Jan van Eyck Academie 
 under the Future Materials programme: one Fashion & Textile Material Fello
 wship and one Future Materials Fellowship\, each lasting 11 months. The pr
 ogramme supports environmentally conscious art and design practices resear
 ching sustainable\, non-toxic\, biobased alternatives to fossil-based or t
 oxic materials. ELIGIBILITY: applicants with an existing research project 
 on sustainable/biobased materials (the Fashion & Textile stream focuses on
  fashion/textile systems\; the Future Materials stream on biobased materia
 ls or processes for broad creative use). Projects should take a systemic p
 erspective on the just transition. Jan van Eyck alumni\, and full-time alu
 mni of the Rijksakademie or De Ateliers\, are not eligible. Fellows develo
 p their project with the Jan van Eyck Labs and Maastricht partners (Textil
 e Innovation Maastricht\; CHILL at Brightlands Chemelot Campus). Apply via
  the respective Jan van Eyck application form.\n\nOrganisation: Jan van Ey
 ck Academie (Future Materials / Future Threads programme\, co-funded by th
 e EU Just Transition Fund)\nLocation: Maastricht\, Netherlands (residency\
 ; fellows must reside within 10km)\nAward: Monthly stipend of EUR 1\,750 (
 80% exempt from income tax) plus an annual working budget of EUR 2\,250\, 
 a private studio apartment\, and access to the Jan van Eyck Labs and exter
 nal partners. Application fee EUR 50 excl. VAT (waived for applicants from
  DAC-list lower-income countries and territories).\nDuration: 11 months (1
 5 January to 15 December 2027)\n\nMore: https://www.janvaneyck.nl/calendar
 /2-material-research-fellowships-2027/
URL:https://www.janvaneyck.nl/calendar/2-material-research-fellowships-2027
 /
LOCATION:Maastricht\, Netherlands (residency\; fellows must reside within 1
 0km)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:artists-futures-fund-breakthrough-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.git
 hub.io
DTSTAMP:20260521T105355Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260612
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260613
SUMMARY:Deadline: Artists' Futures Fund: Breakthrough Artist Fellowship 202
 6-27
DESCRIPTION:Needs-based fellowship from the Artists' Futures Fund bridging 
 the gap from graduation to professional visual-arts practice. ELIGIBILITY:
  recent BA or MA visual-arts graduates (within two years of October 2026) 
 from an AFF partner institution (Cardiff School of Art & Design\, Chichest
 er College Group\, Liverpool Hope\, Loughborough\, Manchester Metropolitan
 \, City of Portsmouth College\, Sunderland\, Swansea College of Art UWTSD)
 \, or a relevant Level 3 UAL Diploma/A Levels from City of Portsmouth Coll
 ege\; must be eligible to live and work in England or Wales\, facing socio
 -economic\, mental and/or physical health barriers\, and able to commit fu
 lly to the 10 months without additional formal study. Applications open 15
  May 2026. Apply via the Artists' Futures Fund support page.\n\nOrganisati
 on: Artists' Futures Fund\nLocation: England and Wales\, UK (in-kind studi
 o space at a partner institution)\nAward: GBP 10\,000 unrestricted bursary
  over the 10-month fellowship\, plus in-kind studio space\, mentorship fro
 m a partner institution\, professional development\, and a co-curated end-
 of-fellowship group showcase. No application fee.\nDuration: 10 months (Oc
 tober 2026 to July 2027)\n\nMore: https://www.artistsfuturesfund.org/oursu
 pport
URL:https://www.artistsfuturesfund.org/oursupport
LOCATION:England and Wales\, UK (in-kind studio space at a partner institut
 ion)
END:VEVENT
